{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17647304","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17647304"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-30T20:43:52+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-30T20:43:52+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"18241"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"18241","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/18241"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"10955"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"76891"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"10955","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/10955"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"18241"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"62396"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"67"},{"type":"tags","id":"71"},{"type":"tags","id":"74"},{"type":"tags","id":"4931"},{"type":"tags","id":"4947"},{"type":"tags","id":"4950"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"25459"},{"type":"contributions","id":"25460"},{"type":"contributions","id":"26473"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"76891","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/76891"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EThe compartment syndrome is an uncommon but important medical condition. It usually affects the limbs and when it does occur, rapid intervention and decompression may be required. This will involve a fasciotomy to relieve pressure on the underlying muscles (Image).\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following is the most common cause of compartment syndrome?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Arterial injury","Bleeding disorders","Contusions","Crush injuries","Fractures"],"correctOptions":[4],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003ECompartment syndrome occurs when increased pressure within a closed muscle compartment compromises circulation and tissue function. The most common cause of compartment syndrome is \u003Cstrong\u003Efractures\u003C/strong\u003E, particularly of the long bones such as the tibia and forearm. The swelling and bleeding associated with fractures can increase compartmental pressure, leading to this condition.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ECrush injuries\u003C/strong\u003E can also lead to compartment syndrome due to direct trauma and swelling, but they are less common than fractures as a cause.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EContusions\u003C/strong\u003E may cause localised swelling and pain but are less likely to result in compartment syndrome compared to fractures.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EBleeding disorders\u003C/strong\u003E can contribute to compartment syndrome if there is significant bleeding into a compartment, but this is not a common cause.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EArterial injury\u003C/strong\u003E can lead to compartment syndrome due to ischaemia-reperfusion injury, but it is less common than fractures as a cause.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Compartment syndrome is most commonly caused by fractures, particularly of the long bones.","Early recognition and intervention in compartment syndrome are crucial to prevent permanent damage.","Compartment syndrome results from increased pressure within a closed muscle compartment, leading to compromised circulation."],"references":["Torlincasi AM, Lopez RA, Waseem M. Acute Compartment Syndrome. 2023 Jan 16. In: StatPearls [Internet]. Treasure Island (FL): StatPearls Publishing; 2024 Jan\u2013. PMID: 28846257.","Dincer, F., \u0026 Samut, G. (2014). Physical examination of the hand. In Hand function: A practical guide to assessment (pp. 23-40). New York, NY: Springer New York","Sud, A., \u0026 Ranjan, R. (2018). Textbook of Orthopaedics, -E-Book. Elsevier Health Sciences","Wojdyla, L., Hughes, T., \u0026 Stelitano, G. (2023). Hand Pathologies. In Textbook of Musculoskeletal Disorders (pp. 675-689). Cham: Springer International Publishing","Mohan, H. (2018). Textbook of pathology. Jaypee Brothers Medical Publishers"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"62396"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"18241"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[{"type":"media","id":"21423"}]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"media","id":"21423","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/media/21423"},"attributes":{"mimeType":"image/jpeg","url":"https://app.emedici.com/storage/media/TaQNFIevZl8ThOVqhnvXCBsVAqNo2A.jpg","thumbUrl":"https://app.emedici.com/storage/media/TaQNFIevZl8ThOVqhnvXCBsVAqNo2A.jpg","isProcessed":true,"width":1500,"height":1125}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"62396","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/62396"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2025-01-05T16:06:35+10:30","updatedAt":"2025-01-05T16:07:18+10:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"10955"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"76891"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"67","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/67"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Basic Science","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"5"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"71","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/71"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Junior","synonyms":null,"description":"Suitable for a junior, pre-clinical medical student","position":0,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"6"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCou